<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 2:14<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2561f160630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>2.</label.designator><headtext>Witnesses</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I259d25a0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.designator>C.</label.designator><headtext>Examination</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f05d1682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>2:14.</label.designator><headtext>In general</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In federal practice, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018087" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRCPR43" w-pub-number="1000600" ID="Id34077807fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Fed. R. Civ. P. Rule 43(a)</cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287018087" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRCRPR26" w-pub-number="1000598" ID="Id34077817fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Fed. R. Crim. P. 26</cite.query> govern the presentation of testimony in court. <eos/><bos/>Both rules provide that <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“(i)n all trials the testimony of witnesses shall be taken orally in open court, unless otherwise provided by an Act of <page no="16"/>Congress”<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/> or other <cite.query w-src-number="0287018087" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRCPR26" w-pub-number="1000600" ID="Id34077827fbf11ea988285db8533e975">federal rules. Rule 26</cite.query> provides that the court has broad discretion in controlling the examination of witnesses. <eos/><bos/>In Georgia, the court has broad discretion in controlling witness examination.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic196df007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] A court may allow an unlisted witness in a criminal trial to testify if the accused is given an opportunity to interview the witness prior to the time he takes the stand.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic196df017fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic196df007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018087" w-serial-number="1930106033" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="Id340c5a27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">National Land &amp; Coal Co. v. Zugar, 171 Ga. 228, 155 S.E. 7 (1930)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018087" w-serial-number="1946103464" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id340c5a57fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Dorsey v. State, 73 Ga. App. 271, 36 S.E.2d 178 (1945)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018087" w-serial-number="1960123796" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id340c5a87fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Fields v. Jackson, 102 Ga. App. 117, 115 S.E.2d 877 (1960)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic196df017fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018087" w-serial-number="1995109975" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id3413ad27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Thrasher v. State, 265 Ga. 401, 456 S.E.2d 578 (1995)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 2:14<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
